    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Salvia africana-lutea</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_9779",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Erect, coastal, perennial shrub with broad, grey leaves that are slightly hairy and aromatic. Golden-brown flowers crowded at ends of branches and have distinctive hooded upper petals that resemble a parrot beak, the long stamens protruding beneath the hood. The rusty coloured saucer-like calyx persists long after the flowers fall.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_9780",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Typically reaches a height of about 2 m.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_9781",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Namaqualand to about Algoa Bay.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_9782",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Coastal species very common on sandy dunes in dryer areas.</p><p>Popular in coastal gardens due to long flowering season and unusual flowers. Flowers also rich in nectar and attract birds and insects.</p><p>Widely used in traditional medicine for respiratory ailments, influenza, gynaecological complaints, fever, headaches and digestive disorders and by settlers as a tea to treat colds, tuberculosis, and chronic bronchitis. Like other <i>Salvia</i> species, the plants are also rich in essentail oils.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_9783",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_9784",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Flowers June to December.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_9785",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>The closely-related Rusty sage <i>S. lanceolata</i> occurs along the west coast as well as further inland and has rusty-red to greyish-blue flowers.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_9786",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        }
